<P>
SOVIETS SEEK DEFICIT CURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A top Soviet economist asserted that the Soviet Union can eliminate its 
$162-billion budget deficit in two or three years by trimming expenditures and 
concentrating on quick-profit ventures. Leonid Abalkin, director of the 
Economics Institute of the Soviet Academy of Sciences, said that erasing the 
red ink is essential to remedy shortages of consumer goods plaguing the nation. 
He said the Soviet state should support businesses that make a quick profit and 
stop financing businesses that won't turn a profit for years. He said $32 
billion could be saved by closing bad businesses and calling off expensive 
construction projects and other huge outlays. A recent government report said 
that one in 10 Soviet enterprises lost money in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
