</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Students conducted a silent protest at ground-breaking ceremonies at Kent State 
University for a scaled-down memorial to students shot by Ohio National 
Guardsmen during 1970 anti-war demonstrations. The students held a banner 
depicting a peace symbol and a dove to protest as inadequate the $100,000 
memorial university trustees unanimously agreed to build. The trustees voted 
Nov. 15 to reduce the cost of the memorial from $1.2 million after a 
fund-raising campaign netted only $40,000. The ground-breaking took place on a 
campus hill near where Guardsmen fired more than 60 shots that hit 13 students 
and killed four. 
